Given a family of kernels `Îº : (n : â„•) â†’ Kernel (Î  i : Iic n, X i) (X (n + 1))`, we define a kernel `ptraj Îº a b : Kernel (Î  i : Iic a, X i) (Î  i : Iic b, X i)`, which is obtained by composing iteratively `Îº a`, `Îº (a + 1)` and so on. This is a building block to prove Ionescu-Tulcea theorem, which in turn allows to define the product of an arbitrary family of probability measures.

From [KolmogorovExtension4](https://github.com/sgouezel/kolmogorov_extension4)

```suggestion
against `ptraj Îº a b`, taking inspiration from `MeasureTheory.lmarginal`.
```

```suggestion
a trajectory up to time `a` and output the distribution of the full trajectory up to time `b`.
```

```suggestion
the distribution of the trajectory in `X (a + 1) Ã— ... Ã— X (b + 1)`.
```

```suggestion
`Î· : Kernel (Î  i : Iic a, X i) â†’ Î  n > a, X n` which given the trajectory up to time `a` outputs
```

```suggestion
and `Îº a âŠ—â‚– Îº (a + 1) âŠ—â‚– ... âŠ—â‚– Îº b` takes the trajectory up to time `a` as input and outputs
```

```suggestion
The Ionescu-Tulcea theorem then tells us that these compositions can be extended into a kernel
```

Not a fan of the `ptraj` name. It's a bit too compressed and hard to understand for my taste. The full name `partialTrajectory` is not that long (although `lmarginalPartialTrajectory` would become long). `partialTraj` is perhaps ok.
It looks like you need to write `IicProdIoc (X := X) a b` at almost every occurence of `IicProdIoc`. You should make `X` explicit and write `IicProdIoc X a b`.

I wondered about that. It's true that when I write lemmas which are only about the map I have to specify `X`, but when I apply it to an element or to a kernel it is not needed. In the end I settled for the implicit version because I think that when it is used for other purposes than its own (which should be the most common use cases) you don't need to specify `X` most of the time, and because in [Set.restrict](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Set/Function.html#Set.restrict) which is similar the argument is implicit. I did the same with `piLE` in #22382 btw. Do you still think I should make it explicit?
